There is also another source from which the true reading has in many cases been retrieved‚ and which throws light on the surpassing merit of P.

This is afforded by the ancient Scholia, which are preserved in P. The corrector, while altering and corrupting the text, did not trouble to alter the Scholium, or note in the margin, which still remains to prove the corruption. Thus in Sat. 1,2 all MSS· read Codri; but the Scholium in P, immediately opposite the text, gives Cordi. Turning to the text of P, we see the word is written Co dri: the inference is clear that the true form of the name is Cordi, and that it was originally found in P, before the corrector erased the r and changed i to ri, as he could easily and neatly do.
